/*
HTML (Hypertext Markup Language) is a markup language used to create and structure web pages. It's the backbone of the web, allowing developers to create content and layout for websites.

Here are some basic HTML concepts to get you started:

HTML is based on a set of tags, which are used to define the structure and content of a web page. Tags are written using angle brackets < >, and they come in pairs - an opening tag and a closing tag.

The basic structure of an HTML document starts with the DOCTYPE declaration, followed by the HTML tag, and then the head and body sections. The head section contains metadata about the document, while the body section contains the visible content of the page.

Headings are important for structuring your content. There are six levels of headings in HTML, from H1 to H6, with H1 being the most important and H6 being the least.

You can add images to your HTML documents using the <img> tag. The tag includes attributes such as src (the URL of the image), alt (a description of the image), and width/height (the dimensions of the image).

Links are an important part of web pages, allowing users to navigate between pages and websites. Links are created using the <a> tag, with the href attribute specifying the URL of the page or resource being linked to.

HTML provides a variety of elements for structuring and styling content. These include lists (<ul>, <ol>, and <li>), tables (<table>, <th>, <tr>, and <td>), and formatting elements such as <em>, <strong>, and <span>.

HTML can be styled using CSS (Cascading Style Sheets), which provides a way to separate the content of a web page from its presentation. CSS can be used to control the layout, colors, fonts, and other visual elements of a web page.

Forms are an important part of web development, allowing users to input data and interact with websites. HTML provides several form elements, such as <input>, <textarea>, and <select>, which can be used to create text boxes, drop-down menus, checkboxes, and radio buttons.

HTML also provides several semantic elements that can be used to define the purpose and meaning of content. These include <header>, <nav>, <main>, <article>, <section>, and <footer>, which can be used to create a structured and accessible web page.

Accessibility is an important consideration in web development, and HTML provides several features that can help make web content more accessible to users with disabilities. These include alt attributes for images, labels for form elements, and the use of semantic elements to provide structure and meaning to web pages.

HTML is constantly evolving, and new versions are released periodically. The current version is HTML5, which introduced several new features such as video and audio tags, canvas elements for creating graphics, and new form elements such as date pickers and sliders.

HTML can be used in combination with other technologies to create dynamic web applications. JavaScript is a popular language used to add interactivity and functionality to web pages, and can be used in combination with HTML and CSS to create complex web applications.

HTML provides several ways to embed media content into web pages, including audio, video, and interactive content such as maps and games. The <audio> and <video> tags allow you to embed audio and video content directly into a web page, while technologies such as WebGL and Canvas allow you to create interactive and animated graphics.

HTML5 introduced several new APIs (Application Programming Interfaces) that allow web developers to create more sophisticated web applications. These include the Geolocation API, which allows web applications to access a user's location, and the Web Storage API, which allows data to be stored locally on a user's device.

HTML can be used to create responsive web design, which allows web pages to adapt to different screen sizes and devices. This is achieved using media queries, which allow you to specify different styles for different screen sizes, and flexible layout techniques such as CSS Grid and Flexbox.

Semantic HTML is an approach to writing HTML that emphasizes the use of semantic elements to provide meaning and structure to web pages. This can help improve accessibility, search engine optimization, and overall code readability.

HTML can also be used in combination with server-side technologies such as PHP and Node.js to create dynamic and data-driven web applications. Server-side technologies allow you to generate HTML on the server before sending it to the client, allowing you to create more complex and interactive web applications.

